clickbait - Leicester (a) Wolves (a) Spurs (a) Man Utd (h) etc some of Liverpool's best performances of the season, coinciding with an upsurge in Firmino and Salah's form. Mane did the biz before the winter break. Also coincided with Joe Gomez hitting top form.

A long season, teams have dips, Liverpool result vs Watford is done, out of the way; FA Cup vs Chelsea, Atletico in the CL etc lets see the Liverpool "slide" on those big nights. Players are only human, motivation and focus was always going to be an issue with a 22pt lead vs the bottom club. The criticism is maybe Klopp should seriously consider starting Curtis Jones, Minamino, Larouchi etc for some remaining league games.

snippet.textDisplay:
What surprise me is that Steve Nicol did not say that in past weeks to warn his social media colleagues' complacency about Liverpool. Steve also praised Liverpool sky high because he was also a Liverpool player. My observation is that after the win over Leicester by 4-0, Liverpool won other games by very thinly margin. And the games against Norwich and Westham witnessed that other teams' managers had cooly analysed Liverpool's tactics and discerned their weaknesses. I always say that when Liverpool's full backs pushed up too much, with Virgil as well, they exposed big space for the opponents lightning counter-attack. Watford had young and quick forwards that exploited Liverpool's background and had so many scoring chances. 3-0 is definitely a wake up call for Liverpool.

Hope Liverpool re-assessed its strategy and re-engineer it a bit.

snippet.textDisplay:
As a Man Utd fan,
I always felt that Liverpool were a team...that run out of gas towards the latter half of the season. The league is sealed....full marks to them...but I still feel that...these same players have been playing insane amount of games in the same formation...that means you extract only so much over the course of 100 to 120 games (across two seasons).
It's very tough to keep the players and the team ticking especially when you have seen so much success with the same set of resources using the same method.
That's what happened to Man City this season. They were phenomenal previous two seasons....but you just run out of ideas....when you experience so much success.
But who knows maybe this is what Liverpool needed to bring that X Factor back into their game.
But despite all of this....it is remarkable how dominant they are in the league. (It hurts as a Man United fan).
